[2] Outbreak summary
Date: Mon 18 Feb 2019 CIDRAP News
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [abridged edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/02/new-cases-katwa-remains-epicenter-ebola-outbreak


With new cases, Katwa [North Kivu] remains epicenter of Ebola outbreak
----------------------------------------------------------------------
More cases recorded today [18 Feb 2019] and over the weekend [16-17 Feb 2019] underscore that Katwa, a city in the eastern reaches of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), remains the current epicenter of the 7-month-long Ebola outbreak in North Kivu and Ituri provinces. On Saturday and Sunday, the DRC's health ministry said there were 2 new Ebola cases in Katwa, and 1 new case in Vuhovi. Today, the ministry reported 2 new cases, one each in Katwa and Butembo.

The new cases raise the outbreak total to 840 cases, of which 775 are confirmed and 65 are probable. There have been 537 deaths during the outbreak, and 185 suspected cases are still under investigation. 7 deaths were recorded over the last 3 days, including 3 community deaths in Katwa, Butembo, and Vuhovi. Community deaths, which occur outside of a hospital or Ebola treatment center, raise the risk of Ebola transmission.

Vaccinations pass the 80 000 mark
---------------------------------
Since August [2018], a total of 80 989 people in the DRC and neighboring countries have been vaccinated with Merck's candidate VSV-EBOV vaccine, including 20 593 in Katwa.

On [Fri 15 Feb 2019], Martin Fayulu, the leader of the Lamuka party, visited Butembo and called for the observance of hygiene measures at a rally. Fayulu considers himself president-elect of the DRC. Fayulu also visited a treatment center in Katwa and praised local health workers for their job.

The visit took place against the backdrop against growing violence in the region, which prompted Doctors Without Borders (MSF) to withdraw nonessential aid workers from Masisi, in North Kivu province. According to Agence France-Presse (AFP), MSF suspended work in the region after gunmen abducted 2 staff members on 8 Feb 2019. Though the region is not currently the site of any Ebola activity, the area is only 100 km [62 mi] from Goma, the capital of North Kivu.

[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

